{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":192,"record_hash":"sha256:12787423c8f92bb1abc7fd11bd2a88d9d4a7f092000ba78a35b4c81e93e0d301","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:28:59.798Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md\n@@\n ## Core Question\n \n Agent Trail should answer:\n@@\n The language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\n to a pull request, branch, review, or change. Do not present related agent data\n as proof of authorship.\n \n+## Current Decisions\n+\n+- MVP entry point: on-demand URL replacement.\n+- Shareable page shape: generated snapshot, not a live view.\n+- Initial access scope: public repositories and public metadata only.\n+- Likely host: Forge, outside the GitButler repository.\n+- Data interpretation: server-side code links and uses `but-agentlog`.\n+\n ## Entry Point\n \n The first expected entry point is a pull request link.\n@@\n Access can come from:\n \n - the repository being public/open source\n - the user authenticating with GitHub\n - a GitButler or Forge installation having repository access\n - a previously published trail snapshot with an allowed share policy\n \n+The first version should focus on public/open-source repositories. Private\n+repository access, GitHub OAuth, GitButler workspace access, and explicit share\n+links can come later.\n+\n This entry point should still respect the publication boundary. Rewriting a URL\n should not automatically expose private captured context. It should create a\n request for an Agent Trail, then show one of:\n@@\n Open design questions:\n \n-- Should on-demand pages be live views or immutable snapshots?\n - Should generated trails be cached automatically?\n - Who can publish or persist the generated result?\n - What should happen when no captured agentlog data exists for the PR?\n - How should GitHub authentication map to GitMeta/Forge access?\n@@\n The important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\n publication and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation should stay\n in `but-agentlog`.\n \n This is still a design-phase decision. Do not start implementing the Forge\n surface until the publication boundary and permissions model are clearer.\n+\n+## Server-Side Metadata Fetch\n+\n+For public v1, the Forge server should be able to create an Agent Trail snapshot\n+on demand by fetching GitMeta metadata for the repository referenced by the PR\n+URL.\n+\n+Example local setup:\n+\n+```ini\n+[remote \"meta\"]\n+  url = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n+  fetch = +refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n+  meta = true\n+  promisor = true\n+  partialclonefilter = blob:none\n+```\n+\n+The server should not assume it can see a developer's local Git remote config.\n+Given a URL like:\n+\n+```text\n+https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n+```\n+\n+the server should resolve the public GitHub repository, then try to fetch the\n+metadata refs from the public repository or a configured metadata remote.\n+\n+Possible first flow:\n+\n+1. parse the PR URL into forge, owner, repo, and PR number\n+2. check that the repository and pull request are public/readable\n+3. create or refresh a server-side bare/cache checkout for the repository\n+4. try to fetch metadata refs, starting with `refs/meta/main`\n+5. if metadata is available, run `but-agentlog` lookup/projection code against\n+   the fetched repository metadata\n+6. generate a review-safe Agent Trail snapshot\n+7. cache or return that snapshot according to the retention policy\n+\n+The low-level metadata fetch can be implemented through `but-agentlog` if the\n+crate grows an appropriate helper, or directly through the `git-meta-lib` /\n+`git-meta` stack if that is the cleaner transport boundary.\n+\n+Recommended split:\n+\n+- `git-meta-lib` or a small shared helper owns GitMeta transport/fetch details\n+- `but-agentlog` owns interpretation of GitButler agentlog keys and records\n+- Forge owns PR URL parsing, access checks, snapshot generation, caching, and UI\n+\n+If the metadata ref is missing or cannot be fetched, the page should show a\n+clear empty state rather than treating the PR as having no agent work:\n+\n+```text\n+No Agent Trail metadata was found for this public pull request.\n+```\n+\n+That distinction matters because \"not fetchable\" and \"no captured sessions\"\n+mean different things.\n \n ## Relationship Model\n \n One pull request may relate to many sessions. One session may relate to many\n@@\n ## Permissions\n \n-Open question: who can view an Agent Trail?\n+First version: public repositories and public metadata only.\n+\n+The server may generate or show an Agent Trail only when it can access the PR\n+and GitMeta metadata without private credentials. Private repository support\n+should be a later design pass.\n+\n+Future policy options:\n \n-Possible policy:\n-\n-- same users who can view the repository\n-- same users who can view the pull request\n - GitButler team/workspace members\n+- same users who can view the repository\n+- same users who can view the pull request\n - explicit share link recipients\n \n-The first version should pick one simple rule and make it obvious. For private\n-repositories, defaulting to repository/PR visibility is probably the least\n-surprising.\n+For private repositories, defaulting to repository/PR visibility is probably the\n+least surprising, but do not build that into v1.\n@@\n ## Pre-Build Decisions\n \n Before implementation starts, settle these product and architecture decisions:\n \n-1. **MVP entry point.** Pick the first supported path: PR description link,\n-   GitHub bot comment, or on-demand URL replacement. Current preference:\n-   on-demand URL replacement plus optional explicit PR link later.\n-2. **Snapshot versus live view.** Decide whether a trail is an immutable\n-   generated snapshot, a live view over current GitMeta data, or a live view\n-   with explicit published snapshots. Current preference: generated snapshots\n-   for anything shareable.\n-3. **Access model.** Define who can view a trail for public repos, private\n-   repos, authenticated GitHub users, GitButler/Forge users, and explicit share\n-   links.\n+1. **Metadata fetch path.** Decide whether Forge fetches metadata through a\n+   helper in `but-agentlog`, a shared GitMeta helper, or direct `git-meta-lib`\n+   usage. Current preference: use GitMeta transport helpers for fetch, then\n+   `but-agentlog` for interpretation.\n+2. **Projection contract.** Define the server-facing output from\n+   `but-agentlog`: related sessions, related turns, record previews, exact\n+   drill-down, relevance evidence, and redaction guarantees.\n+3. **PR-to-target resolution.** Define how a pull request maps to branch,\n+   review, or change targets that `but-agentlog` can query.\n 4. **Publication boundary.** Decide what action turns captured local agentlog\n    data into review-visible Agent Trail data. URL replacement alone must not\n    publish private context.\n-5. **Data access path.** Define how the Forge server obtains repository GitMeta\n-   data, authenticates to remotes, and links the real `but-agentlog` crate.\n-6. **Projection contract.** Define the server-facing output from\n-   `but-agentlog`: related sessions, related turns, record previews, exact\n-   drill-down, relevance evidence, and redaction guarantees.\n-7. **PR-to-target resolution.** Define how a pull request maps to branch,\n-   review, or change targets that `but-agentlog` can query.\n-8. **Session selection and ranking.** Decide which related sessions appear by\n+5. **Session selection and ranking.** Decide which related sessions appear by\n    default, how turns are highlighted, and how the UI explains relevance without\n    claiming authorship.\n-9. **Session browsing UX.** Lock the first-page structure: overview, sessions,\n+6. **Session browsing UX.** Lock the first-page structure: overview, sessions,\n    turn timeline, grouped records, validation, open questions, and raw evidence\n    drawer.\n-10. **Failure states.** Define what the page shows for no access, no captured\n+7. **Failure states.** Define what the page shows for no access, no captured\n     data, weak relation evidence, redaction failures, too much data, and stale\n     GitMeta.\n-11. **Retention and caching.** Decide whether generated trails are stored,\n+8. **Retention and caching.** Decide whether generated trails are stored,\n     invalidated, expired, or rebuilt on demand.\n-12. **Out-of-scope line.** Explicitly exclude compliance/audit guarantees,\n+9. **Out-of-scope line.** Explicitly exclude compliance/audit guarantees,\n     full transcript publishing by default, automatic private publication, and\n     model-generated summaries as the source of truth.\n@@\n ```text\n-GitHub PR URL -> access check -> but-agentlog lookup -> review-safe projection\n--> overview page -> session/turn drill-down\n+GitHub PR URL -> public access check -> metadata fetch -> but-agentlog lookup\n+-> review-safe snapshot -> overview page -> session/turn drill-down\n ```\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:28:59.798Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}